ace from Spanish colonial lookout points in Arizona and Mexico to the Indian wars, when the US cavalry hired Native scouts to track Apache fleeing into Mexico, to the occupation of the Tohono O’odham reservation and the recent launch of robotic bee swarms. Labeled “Optics Valley,” Arizona builds on a global history of violent dispossession and containment of Native peoples and migrants by branding itself as a profitable hub for surveillance. Schaeffer reverses the logic of borders by turning to Indigenous sacredsciences: ancestral land-based practices that are critical to reversing the ecological and social violence of surveillance, extraction, and occupation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBorder crossingxSocial aspectszMexican-American Border Region. 0aBorder securityzMexican-American Border Region. 0aIndian activistszMexican-American Border Region. 0aIndigenous peopleszMexican-American Border RegionxSocial conditions. 0aTraditional ecological knowledgezMexican-American Border Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022565?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022565/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles